  "articleSummary": "The article argues that “just adding more engineers” never speeds up a late software project because coordination costs grow quadratically with team size (n (n‑1)/2), quickly outweighing any extra capacity. It cites classic research—from Brooks’s *Mythical Man‑Month* to modern studies in *Accelerate* and IEEE—that shows larger teams suffer from communication overload, onboarding delays, and higher defect risk, while small, autonomous teams (the “two‑pizza” model) consistently deliver faster and with higher quality. The piece targets engineering managers, CTOs, and senior developers, using a mix of analytical tone and vivid metaphors (e.g., pizza teams, baby‑making analogy) to warn against the fallacy of scaling headcount as a shortcut to meeting deadlines.",
